**Dockerfile Modification**: Change Dockerfile to always get fresh source or copy from mounted location\n4. **Build Script Location**: Execute build.sh directly from mounted volume instead of copying\n\n## OSS-Fuzz Specific Considerations\n- OSS-Fuzz executes build.sh from `$SRC/` (`/src/`)\n- The build.sh must be at `/src/build.sh` \n- Volume mount provides source at `/src/PROJ/`\n- Need to ensure `/src/build.sh` is the modified version\n\n## Recommended Approach\n1. **Option A**: Modify Dockerfile to copy from mounted volume: `RUN cp /src/PROJ/test/fuzzers/build.sh /src/` (but this runs during build, not runtime)\n2. **Option B**: Modify the entrypoint or command to copy build.sh at container startup\n3. **Option C**: Change OSS-Fuzz to execute build.sh from `/src/PROJ/test/fuzzers/` instead of `/src/`\n4. **Option D**: Use Docker build arguments to bust cache for the clone layer\n\n## Implementation Strategy\nGiven the constraints, the most practical solution is to modify the Dockerfile or build process to ensure the modified build.sh is used. Since we can\'t change OSS-Fuzz\'s execution pattern, we need to ensure `/src/build.sh` is our modified version.\n\n## Validation\nAfter fix, verify:\n1. Build log shows path resolution code executing\n2. `cd curl` succeeds\n3. Build proceeds beyond the curl directory error\n\n--- 【LESSONS FROM PREVIOUS ATTEMPTS】 ---\n- [Attempt 2] Fix didn\'t work because Docker image was cached and used old build.sh. The Dockerfile copies build.sh during image build (RUN cp test/fuzzers/build.sh $SRC/), but Docker build uses cached layers. Modified source code isn\'t reflected in the executed script. Need to either: 1) Force Docker rebuild without cache, 2) Modify Dockerfile to always copy fresh build.sh, or 3) Modify the runtime execution to use updated script. This is a Docker caching issue, not a logic issue with the fix itself.\n- [Attempt 1] Build script has incorrect path assumptions. It expects to run from PROJ directory where curl