  - STATE_UPDATE: {'solution_plan': '[HYBRID]: Strategy guided by General Principles (pkg-config environment setup for dependency resolution), but implementation details are derived from code analysis of curl\'s configure script behavior and OpenSSL installation paths.\n\n**Explanation of the fix:**\n1. **Removed `libssl-dev` from apt-get install**: Since we\'re building OpenSSL 3.0 from source, we don\'t need the system OpenSSL 1.1.1 development files. This prevents pkg-config from finding the wrong OpenSSL.\n\n2. **Added PKG_CONFIG_PATH, CPPFLAGS, and LDFLAGS**: These environment variables ensure that curl\'s configure script finds our OpenSSL 3.0 installation:\n   - `PKG_CONFIG_PATH=/usr/local/ssl3/lib/pkgconfig:$PKG_CONFIG_PATH`: Tells pkg-config to look in our OpenSSL 3.0 installation directory\n   - `CPPFLAGS="-I/usr/local/ssl3/include $CPPFLAGS"`: Adds our OpenSSL 3.0 include directory to compiler flags\n   - `LDFLAGS="-L/usr/local/ssl3/lib $LDFLAGS"`: Adds our OpenSSL 3.0 library directory to linker flags\n\n3. **Updated EXTRA_LIBS**: Added `-L/usr/local/ssl3/lib` to ensure the linker finds our OpenSSL 3.0 libraries at link time.\n\n4. **Applied changes in both Dockerfile sed command and directly in build.sh**: This ensures consistency whether the Dockerfile modifies build.sh or we use the source build.sh directly.\n\nThis fix addresses the root cause identified in the reflection journal: curl\'s configure script prefers pkg-config detection over the `--with-ssl` flag. By setting `PKG_CONFIG_PATH` and removing the system `libssl-dev` package, we ensure curl finds and uses our OpenSSL 3.0 installation.'}
